{"title_page": "Fiona Bruce (politician)", "text_new": "{{for|the newsreader|Fiona Bruce}}{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Fiona Bruce\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Fiona Bruce MP crop 2.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Congleton (UK Parliament constituency)|Congleton]]\n| majority = 18,591 (32.5%)\n| term_start = 6 May 2010\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Ann Winterton|Ann, Lady Winterton]]\n| successor = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1957|3|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_name = Fiona Claire Riley\n| birth_place = [[Wick, Caithness]], [[Scotland]]\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| party = [[Conservative party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Manchester]]\n| spouse = Richard John Bruce\n| children = 2\n| website = [https://www.fionabruce.org.uk Official website]<br />[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/fiona-bruce/3958 parliament..fiona-bruce]\n}}\n'''Fiona Claire Bruce'''<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59418 |page=8740 |date=13 May 2010 }}</ref> (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' '''Riley'''; born 26 March 1957) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician who was elected the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Congleton (UK Parliament constituency)|Congleton]] in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/fiona_bruce/congleton|title=Fiona Bruce|work=theyworkforyou.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/b18.stm|title=BBC News - Election 2010 - Constituency - Congleton|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nFiona Claire Riley was born on 26 March 1957 in [[Wick, Caithness|Wick]], [[Caithness]], [[Scotland]] to Allan Stewart and Greta Riley (n\u00e9e Scott).<ref name=UKWW>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-251099|title=Bruce, Fiona Claire|publisher=A & C Black|accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref> She attended [[Burnley Grammar School|Burnley High School for Girls]], and the [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] [[Howell's School, Llandaff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/gdst/docs/gdst-annual-review-2015|title=The GDST Difference - Annual Review 2015|publisher=GDST|date=7 April 2016|accessdate=3 November 2019|page=15}}</ref> Riley then studied law at the [[University of Manchester]] and further studies at [[Chester|Chester Law College]].\n\nShe was admitted as a [[solicitor]] in 1981, and has been [[senior partner]] of the firm, Fiona Bruce & Co, since its formation in 1988.\n\n==Political career==\n\nBruce was elected in 2004 to [[Warrington Borough Council]], on which she served as Executive Member for Finance from 2006\u20132009. She stepped down from the Council upon her election to Parliament in 2010.\n\nShe had unsuccessfully contested [[Warrington South (UK Parliament constituency)|Warrington South]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], finishing second to the sitting Labour MP, [[Helen Southworth]].\n\nShe was awarded the title Small Businesswoman of the Year in 2003 and gained a place on the [[A-List (Conservative)|Conservative A-List]] in 2006.<ref>*[http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2006/05/as_promised_thi.html Who is on the A-list?] at conservativehome web site</ref><ref>[http://colin-ross.org.uk/news/000729/conservative_alist_and_selections.html Conservative A-List and selections] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328220043/http://colin-ross.org.uk/news/000729/conservative_alist_and_selections.html |date=28 March 2010 }} dated 4 June 2006 at colin-ross.org.uk</ref>\n\nFollowing her selection as the Conservative Party candidate for the constituency, she denied that she had been chosen as a result of an orchestrated campaign by religious groups sympathetic to her [[evangelical Christian]] beliefs.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/12400596-16ac-11df-aa09-00144feab49a.html#axzz1HujKYPbK |title=Christian Tories rewrite party doctrine|newspaper= The Financial Times|accessdate= 28 March 2011}}</ref> Bruce is an [[Evangelical Alliance]] council member and describes \"defending and fighting for the sanctity of human life\" as her priority in Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Question Time|url=http://www.eauk.org/idea/question-time.cfm|website=Evangelical Alliance|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe has been a member of the Scottish Affairs Select Committee since 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/fiona-bruce/35510 |title=Fiona Bruce |publisher=parliament.uk |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, Bruce introduced an amendment to the [[Serious Crime Bill 2014]] to make abortion on the grounds of the sex of the baby illegal.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bruce|first1=Fiona|title=Sex-selective abortion is unacceptable \u2013 we must make the law clear|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2014/10/fiona-bruce-mp-sex-selective-abortion-is-unacceptable-we-must-make-the-law-clear.html|website=Conservative Home|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Ditum|first1=Sarah|title=Against the Fiona Bruce amendment: why feminists should oppose the ban on sex-selective abortion|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/02/against-fiona-bruce-amendment-why-feminists-should-oppose-ban-sex-selective|accessdate=19 March 2015|magazine=New Statesman|date=20 February 2015}}</ref> The amendment was rejected by 292 votes to 201.<ref>{{cite news|title=MPs reject backbench bid to amend abortion laws|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-31596968|accessdate=19 March 2015|publisher=BBC|date=24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nBruce supported [[Brexit]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough|first1=Tom|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence?|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|accessdate=11 October 2016|work=The Spectator|date=16 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Bruce said the government's decision not to ban anti-abortion protests outside clinics was a \"win for mothers\".<ref name=inews-20180914>{{cite news |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/tory-mp-anti-abortion-protest-ban/ |title=Tory MP Fiona Bruce says not banning anti-abortion protests is a 'win for mothers' |last=Chaplain |first=Chloe |website=i News |date=14 September 2018 |accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Bruce chaired an inquiry for the [[Conservative Party Human Rights Commission]] into prostitution, which concluded that replacing the [[Prostitution in the United Kingdom|present soliciting laws]] with laws making paying for sexual services a criminal offence is the most effective way of reducing the size of the prostitution market.<ref name=guardian-20190729>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/jul/29/how-can-the-tories-moralising-report-on-prostitution-completely-ignore-austerity |title=How can the Tories' moralising report on prostitution completely ignore austerity? |last=Mullin |first=Frankie |newspaper=The Guardian |date=29 July 2019 |accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20190725>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/07/25/decriminalise-prostitutes-selling-sex-prosecute-buyers-says/ |title=Decriminalise prostitutes selling sex but prosecute buyers, says Tory commission |last=Hymas |first=Charles |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=25 July 2019 |accessdate=1 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nShe married Richard John Bruce in 1990, and they have two sons.<ref name=UKWW/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Bruce_Fiona.aspx Fiona Bruce MP] Conservative Party profile\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091123102819/http://www.congletonconservatives.com/ Congleton Conservatives]\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = fiona-bruce/3958 | hansardcurr = <!-- 5527 --> | guardian = 9400/fiona-bruce | publicwhip = Fiona_Bruce | theywork = fiona_bruce | record = Fiona-Bruce/Congleton/1232 | bbc = 35510.stm | journalisted = }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ann Winterton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Congleton (UK Parliament constituency)|Congleton]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{North West Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bruce, Fiona}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Wick, Caithness]]\n[[Category:People from Congleton]]\n[[Category:Scottish evangelicals]]\n[[Category:People educated at Howell's School Llandaff]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the newsreader|Fiona Bruce}}{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Fiona Bruce\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Fiona Bruce MP crop 2.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Congleton (UK Parliament constituency)|Congleton]]\n| majority = 18,591 (32.5%)\n| term_start = 6 May 2010\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Ann Winterton|Ann, Lady Winterton]]\n| successor = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1957|3|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_name = Fiona Claire Riley\n| birth_place = [[Wick, Caithness]], [[Scotland]]\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| party = [[Conservative party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Manchester]]\n| spouse = Richard John Bruce\n| children = 2\n| website = [https://www.fionabruce.org.uk Official website]<br />[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/fiona-bruce/3958 parliament..fiona-bruce]\n}}\n'''Fiona Claire Bruce'''<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59418 |page=8740 |date=13 May 2010 }}</ref> (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' '''Riley'''; born 26 March 1957) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician who was elected the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Congleton (UK Parliament constituency)|Congleton]] in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/fiona_bruce/congleton|title=Fiona Bruce|work=theyworkforyou.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/b18.stm|title=BBC News - Election 2010 - Constituency - Congleton|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nFiona Claire Riley was born on 26 March 1957 in [[Wick, Caithness|Wick]], [[Caithness]], [[Scotland]] to Allan Stewart and Greta Riley (n\u00e9e Scott).<ref name=UKWW>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-251099|title=Bruce, Fiona Claire|publisher=A & C Black|accessdate=3 November 2019}}</ref> She attended [[Burnley Grammar School|Burnley High School for Girls]], and the [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] [[Howell's School, Llandaff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/gdst/docs/gdst-annual-review-2015|title=The GDST Difference - Annual Review 2015|publisher=GDST|date=7 April 2016|accessdate=3 November 2019|page=15}}</ref> Riley then studied law at the [[University of Manchester]] and further studies at [[Chester|Chester Law College]].\n\nShe was admitted as a [[solicitor]] in 1981, and has been [[senior partner]] of the firm, Fiona Bruce & Co, since its formation in 1988.\n\n==Political career==\n\nBruce was elected in 2004 to [[Warrington Borough Council]], on which she served as Executive Member for Finance from 2006-2009. She stepped down from the Council upon her election to Parliament in 2010.\n\nShe had unsuccessfully contested [[Warrington South (UK Parliament constituency)|Warrington South]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], finishing second to the sitting Labour MP, [[Helen Southworth]].\n\nShe was awarded the title Small Businesswoman of the Year in 2003 and gained a place on the [[A-List (Conservative)|Conservative A-List]] in 2006.<ref>*[http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2006/05/as_promised_thi.html Who is on the A-list?] at conservativehome web site</ref><ref>[http://colin-ross.org.uk/news/000729/conservative_alist_and_selections.html Conservative A-List and selections] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100328220043/http://colin-ross.org.uk/news/000729/conservative_alist_and_selections.html |date=28 March 2010 }} dated 4 June 2006 at colin-ross.org.uk</ref>\n\nFollowing her selection as the Conservative Party candidate for the constituency, she denied that she had been chosen as a result of an orchestrated campaign by religious groups sympathetic to her [[evangelical Christian]] beliefs.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/12400596-16ac-11df-aa09-00144feab49a.html#axzz1HujKYPbK |title=Christian Tories rewrite party doctrine|newspaper= The Financial Times|accessdate= 28 March 2011}}</ref> Bruce is an [[Evangelical Alliance]] council member and describes \"defending and fighting for the sanctity of human life\" as her priority in Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Question Time|url=http://www.eauk.org/idea/question-time.cfm|website=Evangelical Alliance|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe has been a member of the Scottish Affairs Select Committee since 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/fiona-bruce/35510 |title=Fiona Bruce |publisher=parliament.uk |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, Bruce introduced an amendment to the [[Serious Crime Bill 2014]] to make abortion on the grounds of the sex of the baby illegal.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bruce|first1=Fiona|title=Sex-selective abortion is unacceptable \u2013 we must make the law clear|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/platform/2014/10/fiona-bruce-mp-sex-selective-abortion-is-unacceptable-we-must-make-the-law-clear.html|website=Conservative Home|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Ditum|first1=Sarah|title=Against the Fiona Bruce amendment: why feminists should oppose the ban on sex-selective abortion|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/02/against-fiona-bruce-amendment-why-feminists-should-oppose-ban-sex-selective|accessdate=19 March 2015|magazine=New Statesman|date=20 February 2015}}</ref> The amendment was rejected by 292 votes to 201.<ref>{{cite news|title=MPs reject backbench bid to amend abortion laws|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-31596968|accessdate=19 March 2015|publisher=BBC|date=24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nBruce supported [[Brexit]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough|first1=Tom|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence?|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|accessdate=11 October 2016|work=The Spectator|date=16 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Bruce said the government's decision not to ban anti-abortion protests outside clinics was a \"win for mothers\".<ref name=inews-20180914>{{cite news |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/politics/tory-mp-anti-abortion-protest-ban/ |title=Tory MP Fiona Bruce says not banning anti-abortion protests is a 'win for mothers' |last=Chaplain |first=Chloe |website=i News |date=14 September 2018 |accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Bruce chaired an inquiry for the [[Conservative Party Human Rights Commission]] into prostitution, which concluded that replacing the [[Prostitution in the United Kingdom|present soliciting laws]] with laws making paying for sexual services a criminal offence is the most effective way of reducing the size of the prostitution market.<ref name=guardian-20190729>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/jul/29/how-can-the-tories-moralising-report-on-prostitution-completely-ignore-austerity |title=How can the Tories' moralising report on prostitution completely ignore austerity? |last=Mullin |first=Frankie |newspaper=The Guardian |date=29 July 2019 |accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20190725>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/07/25/decriminalise-prostitutes-selling-sex-prosecute-buyers-says/ |title=Decriminalise prostitutes selling sex but prosecute buyers, says Tory commission |last=Hymas |first=Charles |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=25 July 2019 |accessdate=1 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nShe married Richard John Bruce in 1990, and they have two sons.<ref name=UKWW/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Bruce_Fiona.aspx Fiona Bruce MP] Conservative Party profile\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091123102819/http://www.congletonconservatives.com/ Congleton Conservatives]\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = fiona-bruce/3958 | hansardcurr = <!-- 5527 --> | guardian = 9400/fiona-bruce | publicwhip = Fiona_Bruce | theywork = fiona_bruce | record = Fiona-Bruce/Congleton/1232 | bbc = 35510.stm | journalisted = }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ann Winterton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Congleton (UK Parliament constituency)|Congleton]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{North West Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bruce, Fiona}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Wick, Caithness]]\n[[Category:People from Congleton]]\n[[Category:Scottish evangelicals]]\n[[Category:People educated at Howell's School Llandaff]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2006-2009 \u2192 2006\u20132009", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiona_Bruce_(politician)"}
