{"title_page": "Bob Blackman", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Bob Blackman\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Bob Blackman MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Blackman in 2020\n| office = Executive Secretary of the [[1922 Committee]]\n| leader = [[David Cameron]]<br />[[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 17 May 2012\n| alongside = [[Nigel Evans]] (2017-2020)\n| successor = \n| predecessor = [[Peter Bone]] &<br />[[Christopher Chope|Sir Christopher Chope]]\n| 1blankname = Chairman\n| 1namedata = [[Graham Brady|Sir Graham Brady]]<br />[[Cheryl Gillan]]<br />[[Charles Walker (British politician)|Charles Walker]]\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]]\n| majority2 = 8,170 (16.5%)\n| predecessor2 = [[Tony McNulty]]\n| successor2 = \n| term_start2 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end2 = \n| constituency_AM3 = [[Brent and Harrow (London Assembly constituency)|Brent and Harrow]]\n| assembly3 = London\n| term_start3 = 10 June 2004\n| term_end3 = 1 May 2008\n| predecessor3 = [[Toby Harris, Baron Harris of Haringey|Toby Harris]]\n| successor3 = [[Navin Shah]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1956|04|26}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/37675.stm |title=Bob Blackman MP |publisher=BBC |work=BBC Democracy Live |date= |accessdate=25 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917000831/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/37675.stm |archive-date=17 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Metropolitan Borough of Kensington|Kensington]], London, England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Nicola Blackman\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = [[Wembley]], [[London]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Liverpool]]<br /><small> ([[Physics]] and [[Mathematics]] <br />[[Bachelor's degree]])</small>\n| occupation = \n| profession = [[BT Group|BT]]<br />[[telecommunications]] engineer\n| signature = \n| website = [http://www.bobblackmanmp.com/ bobblackmanmp.com]<br />[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/bob-blackman/4005 parliament.uk biography]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Robert John Blackman''' (born 26 April 1956) is a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician serving as the Executive Secretary of the [[1922 Committee]] since 2012 (serving jointly with [[Nigel Evans]] until 8th January 2020 when Nigel became 2nd Deputy Chairman of Ways and Means),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18093877|title=New faces on Tory 1922 committee|date=17 May 2012|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=30 December 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517085542/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18093877|archive-date=17 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> and has served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]] since [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]. He was also the [[Greater London Assembly]] member for [[Brent and Harrow (London Assembly constituency)|Brent & Harrow]] between 2004 and 2008.\n\nHe is the recipient of India's highly prestigious award [[Padma Shri]] 2020 for his work in the field of public affairs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Padma Awards 2020 Announced |url=https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=197647 |website=pib.gov.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Desk |first1=The Hindu Net |title=Full list of 2020 Padma awardees |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/full-list-of-2020-padma-awardees/article30656841.ece |work=The Hindu |date=26 January 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nHe studied at the [[University of Liverpool]], where he was president of the [[students' union]]. He joined the sales team of Burroughs Machines (later [[Unisys]]) on graduation. He worked in various sales and management positions for [[BT Group plc|BT]] and worked at their training school in [[Milton Keynes]] as a tutor<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://www.bobblackmanmp.com/about/biography|website=Bob Blackman|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205213929/http://bobblackmanmp.com/about/biography|archive-date=5 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and later as a Regulatory Compliance Manager for BT<ref name=\"DeHaviland\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dehavilland.co.uk/VERTICALS/userlogin2.aspx?ReturnUrl=%2fVERTICALS%2fMonitor%2fMoStart.aspx%3fitems%3d18540349&items=18540349|title=Blackman responds to statement on the Leveson Inquiry|work=DeHaviland|accessdate=7 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105012508/http://www.dehavilland.co.uk/VERTICALS/userlogin2.aspx?ReturnUrl=%2fVERTICALS%2fMonitor%2fMoStart.aspx%3fitems%3d18540349&items=18540349|archive-date=5 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> until his election to Parliament.\n\n==Political career==\nBlackman unsuccessfully stood as the Conservative candidate in the Tokyngton ward of [[London Borough of Brent]] Council in 1986. Four years later, he stood in the [[Preston, London|Preston ward]] and was elected; he retained the seat until 2010, when he did not stand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Brent-1964-2010.pdf|title=London Borough of Brent Election Results 1964-2010|publisher=Plymouth University|accessdate=7 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142902/http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Brent-1964-2010.pdf|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He was the leader of the Conservative group on Brent council from 1990 to 2010, having been council leader between 1991 and 1996, when his party lost control of the Council. From June 2006 to May 2010, he was Deputy Leader of Brent Council, the Conservatives having formed a coalition with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].\n\nHe unsuccessfully stood as the Conservative Party parliamentary candidate for [[Brent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent South]] at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 election]], for [[Bedford (UK Parliament constituency)|Bedford]] at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 election]], and for [[Brent North (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent North]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 election]].\n\nHe unsuccessfully stood as the Conservative Party candidate for the constituency seat of [[Brent and Harrow (London Assembly constituency)|Brent and Harrow]] of the [[London Assembly]] at the [[2000 London Assembly election|2000 elections]], losing to the Labour Party candidate [[Toby Harris]]. However, he subsequently defeated Harris at the [[2004 London Assembly election|2004 assembly elections]] and was elected as the Conservative's [[Whip (politics)|Group Whip]] on the London Assembly. In the [[2008 London Assembly election|2008 elections]], Blackman lost his seat to the Labour candidate, [[Navin Shah]] by a 1,649 votes.<ref name=\"BBC2008lonresult\">{{Cite news | title = Brent & Harrow 2008 Election Result | publisher = BBC News | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/bsp/hi/elections/london/08/html/3.stm | date = 11 June 2008 | accessdate = 8 January 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120425062400/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/bsp/hi/elections/london/08/html/3.stm | archive-date = 25 April 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\nIn the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], Blackman gained the [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]] constituency from [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour's]] [[Tony McNulty]]. He was subsequently re-elected in 2015 and 2017.\n\nIn 2010 he was elected a member of the [[Communities and Local Government Committee|Communities and Local Government Select Committee]].<ref name=\"ParliamentBlackman\">{{cite web | title = Communities and Local Government Select Committee | publisher = UK Parliament | work = UK Parliament Website | url = http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/communities-and-local-government-committee/membership/ | date =  | accessdate = 8 January 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120118050938/http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/communities-and-local-government-committee/membership/ | archive-date = 18 January 2012 | url-status = live }}[]</ref> and was elected Secretary of the [[1922 Committee]] in 2015.<ref name=\"ConHome\">{{cite web | title = 1922 Committee Results | publisher = Conservative Home | work = Conservative Home Website | url = http://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2015/06/the-full-results-of-the-latest-1922-committee-election.html | date =  | accessdate = 25 April 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170426152225/http://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2015/06/the-full-results-of-the-latest-1922-committee-election.html | archive-date = 26 April 2017 | url-status = live }}</ref> In Parliament, Blackman currently serves on the Procedure Committee, the Backbench Business Committee and the Housing, Communities and Local Government Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/bob-blackman/4005|title=Bob Blackman MP|publisher=GOV.UK|accessdate=7 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143858/https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/bob-blackman/4005|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, the Labour Party unsuccessfully proposed an amendment in Parliament that would have required private landlords to make their homes \"fit for human habitation\". According to Parliament's register of interests, Blackman was one of 72 Conservative MPs voting against the amendment who personally derived an income from renting out property. The Conservative Government had responded to the amendment that they believed homes should be fit for human habitation but did not want to pass the new law that would explicitly require it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tories vote down law requiring landlords make their homes fit for human habitation|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tories-vote-down-law-requiring-landlords-make-their-homes-fit-for-human-habitation-a6809691.html|work=[[The Independent|Independent]]|accessdate=18 September 2018|date=9 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906032222/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tories-vote-down-law-requiring-landlords-make-their-homes-fit-for-human-habitation-a6809691.html|archive-date=6 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBlackman supported [[Brexit]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough|first1=Tom|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence?|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|accessdate=11 October 2016|work=The Spectator|date=16 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502030758/https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|archive-date=2 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He subsequently joined the [[European Research Group]] \u2013 the primary Eurosceptic lobbying group within Parliament, which is currently chaired by [[Jacob Rees-Mogg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/371977491/Letter-from-European-Research-Group-to-PM-May#from_embed|title=Letter from European Research Group to PM May|accessdate=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302201212/https://www.scribd.com/document/371977491/Letter-from-European-Research-Group-to-PM-May#from_embed|archive-date=2 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBlackman is an Officer of the [[Conservative Friends of Israel]] group and has been part of several delegations to Israel,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.cfoi.co.uk/Delegations/RecentDelegations/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-07-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727005934/http://www2.cfoi.co.uk/Delegations/RecentDelegations/ |archivedate=27 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> including during the [[Operation Defensive Shield]] conflict when he visited for an Israeli military briefing on the Iron Dome defence system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/30/tory-mps-visit-israel-condemned-bad-timing|title=Tory MPs' visit to Israel condemned as bad timing|first1=Rowena|last1=Mason|date=30 July 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=16 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126110223/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/30/tory-mps-visit-israel-condemned-bad-timing|archive-date=26 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the Compliance Officer for the [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority]] (IPSA) made a judgement that Blackman had submitted 732 inaccurate mileage claims.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Datoo|first1=Siraj|title=Tory MP Pays Back His Expenses After Making 734 \"Inaccurate\" Claims|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-31129900|publisher=BBC|date=4 February 2015|access-date=20 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109230544/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-31129900|archive-date=9 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to IPSA he claimed up to 10 miles for a 2-mile journey, making him the highest mileage MP, claiming almost twice the mileage as the 10 next highest MPs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11389305/Tory-MP-Bob-Blackmans-700-inaccurate-expenses-claims.html|title=Tory MP Bob Blackman's 700 'inaccurate expenses claims'|work=Daily Telegraph|date=4 February 2015|accessdate=4 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915122542/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11389305/Tory-MP-Bob-Blackmans-700-inaccurate-expenses-claims.html|archive-date=15 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBlackman has been accused{{by whom|date=January 2019}} of stirring up racial tensions as a result of racial bias for hosting Tapan Gosh, an anti-Islam campaigner from India at a [[House of Commons]] event in October 2017,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/anti-islam-tapan-ghosh-bob-blackman-rohingya-muslims-a8020656.html|title=Anti-Islam extremist who praised Rohingya massacre hosted in Commons|date=26 October 2017|work=The Independent|accessdate=30 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109114207/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/anti-islam-tapan-ghosh-bob-blackman-rohingya-muslims-a8020656.html|archive-date=9 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as sharing Islamophobic posts on Twitter by far-right activist [[Tommy Robinson (activist)|Tommy Robinson]] and being a member of numerous anti-Islam groups on Facebook.<ref name=\"Fisher2018\">{{cite news |last1=Fisher |first1=Lucy |title=Muslim Council of Britain demands inquiry into Tory 'Islamophobia' |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/muslim-council-of-britain-demands-inquiry-into-tory-islamophobia-jb6tw88sk |accessdate=14 August 2018 |work=The Times |date=31 May 2018 |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815055259/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/muslim-council-of-britain-demands-inquiry-into-tory-islamophobia-jb6tw88sk |archive-date=15 August 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> These comments and others by Conservative candidates and representatives led the [[Muslim Council of Britain]] to call for an [[Islamophobia in the UK Conservative Party#Calls for an independent inquiry|independent inquiry into alleged Islamophobia in the Conservative Party]].<ref name=\"Fisher2018\" />\n\nIn March 2019, Blackman was among a group of MPs who argued for a number of measures to encourage people to quit [[smoking]] and prevent young people from taking it up, including raising the legal [[smoking age]] to 21 and introducing a levy on [[Big Tobacco|large tobacco companies]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Jamie Doward |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/mar/02/raise-legal-smoking-age-to-21-say-mps |title=MPs call for legal smoking age to be raised to 21 &#124; Society |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2019-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191024134235/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/mar/02/raise-legal-smoking-age-to-21-say-mps |archive-date=24 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Blackman expressed his support for Indian [[Narendra Modi|Prime Minister Narendra Modi]] revoking [[Article 370 of the Constitution of India]], calling the article an \"anomaly\", adding that \"[[Kashmiri Pandits]] must be guaranteed right of return after they were the victims of ethnic cleansing\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/17831849.bob-blackman-harrow-east-mp-shares-thoughts-article-370/ |title=Bob Blackman, Harrow East MP, shares thoughts on Article 370 |publisher=Harrow Times |date=2019-08-12 |accessdate=2019-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191024104540/https://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/17831849.bob-blackman-harrow-east-mp-shares-thoughts-article-370/ |archive-date=24 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Campaigns==\nBlackman called for the adoption of plain packaging legislation for cigarettes,<ref name=\"Emma Innes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10081729.Harrow_MP_calls_for_cigarettes_to_be_sold_in_plain_packets/|title=Harrow MP calls for cigarettes to be sold in plain packets (From Harrow Times)|last=Emma Innes|date=30 November 2012|accessdate=7 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031019/http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10081729.Harrow_MP_calls_for_cigarettes_to_be_sold_in_plain_packets/|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and supported Cameron's plan calling for energy companies to provide simplified energy bills to their customers.<ref name=\"energy\">{{cite news|url=http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10060598.Harrow_East_MP_supports_government_energy_plans/|title=Harrow East MP supports government energy plans (From Harrow Times)|last=Emma Innes|date=21 November 2012|accessdate=7 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234819/http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10060598.Harrow_East_MP_supports_government_energy_plans/|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\nOn 1 July 2015, Blackman was elected Chair of the All Party Political Group on Smoking and Health, after serving as its Secretary for several years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blackman|first1=Bob|title=Delighted to be elected Chairman of APPG for Action on Smoking & Health|url=https://twitter.com/bobblackmanmp/status/616392556990103553|publisher=Twitter|date=2 July 2015|access-date=2 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305214317/https://twitter.com/bobblackmanmp/status/616392556990103553|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170106/smoking-and-health.htm|title=Register Of All-Party Parliamentary Groups [as at 6 January 2017]|work=Parliament.uk|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323142850/https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170106/smoking-and-health.htm|archive-date=23 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] announced his approval for same-sex marriage.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{Cite journal | title = Gay marriage: David Cameron backs church role | publisher = BBC | journal = BBC News | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20642428 | date = 6 December 2012 | accessdate = 6 December 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121207192535/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20642428 | archive-date = 7 December 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref> In response, on 7 December 2012, Blackman told the [[BBC News Channel]] that David Cameron's backing of religious same-sex marriages was wrong \"on principle\" and that marriage had to be \"between one man and one woman\".<ref>Joe Murphy, \"Anti-homosexual Section 28 was right for schools, says Tory MP\", ''London Evening Standard'', 10 December 2012 [https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/antihomosexual-section-28-was-right-for-schools-says-tory-mp-8398942.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150601025652/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/antihomosexual-section-28-was-right-for-schools-says-tory-mp-8398942.html |date=1 June 2015 }}</ref> According to the ''Harrow Times'', he was accused of [[hypocrisy]] by a former fellow Brent council colleague who claimed she had an 11-year affair with him whilst he was married.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10112195.MP_at_heart_of_national_newspaper_storm|title=Harrow East MP Bob Blackman at heart of national newspaper storm|author=Emma Innes|work=Harrow Times|date=17 December 2012|accessdate=25 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126042509/http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10112195.MP_at_heart_of_national_newspaper_storm/|archive-date=26 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 February 2013, Bob Blackman voted against the bill in the House of Commons Second Reading vote on marriage equality in Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130205/debtext/130205-0004.htm|title=The House of Commons.2013.Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Bill 2012\u20132013.|website=publications.parliament.uk|access-date=12 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115021159/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130205/debtext/130205-0004.htm|archive-date=15 November 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, when the Conservative Party launched its consultation into legalising same-sex marriages, Blackman suggested that [[David Cameron]] should resurrect [[Section 28]], stating that he strongly believed that \"Section 28 was the right rules to have in school so that we should not in any way shape or form promote same-sex relationships\" and said he would be \"very opposed\" to seeing teachers being forced to say same-sex relationships are equivalent to heterosexual relationships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/12/07/tory-mp-bob-blackman-cameron-should-be-re-introducing-section-28-not-letting-gays-marry/|title=Tory MP Bob Blackman: Cameron should be re-introducing Section 28 not letting gays marry|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131224545/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/12/07/tory-mp-bob-blackman-cameron-should-be-re-introducing-section-28-not-letting-gays-marry/|archive-date=31 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Blackman was one of 21 MPs who voted against LGBT inclusive sex and relationship education in English schools.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/education/lgbt-sex-relationship-education-mps-support/ |title=MPs vote for LGBT inclusive sex and relationship education from primary school |publisher=inews |date= |accessdate=2019-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330104814/https://inews.co.uk/news/education/lgbt-sex-relationship-education-mps-support/ |archive-date=30 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/21-mps-who-voted-against-14198149 |title=Archived copy |access-date=30 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330093652/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/21-mps-who-voted-against-14198149 |archive-date=30 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://commonsvotes.digiminster.com/Divisions/Details/650#noes |title=Draft Relationships Education, Relationships and Sex Education and Health Education (England) Regulations 2019 - CommonsVotes |publisher=Commonsvotes.digiminster.com |date=2019-03-27 |accessdate=2019-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329025226/https://commonsvotes.digiminster.com/Divisions/Details/650#noes |archive-date=29 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he was drawn second in the annual Parliamentary ballot for a [[Private Member's Bill]] and subsequently put together a Homelessness Reduction Bill in partnership with national homelessness charity, [[Crisis (charity)|Crisis]].<ref name=\"Crisis Report\">{{cite web | title = No One Turned Away | publisher = Crisis | url = https://community.crisis.org.uk/no-one-turned-away/home | date =  | accessdate = 25 April 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170426151613/https://community.crisis.org.uk/no-one-turned-away/home | archive-date = 26 April 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref> It was the first Private Member's Bill to be supported by a Select Committee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Homelessness Reduction Bill supported by Committee|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/communities-and-local-government-committee/news-parliament-2015/homelessness-reduction-bill-report-published-16-17/|work=[[UK Parliament]]|date=14 October 2016|access-date=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426152201/http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/communities-and-local-government-committee/news-parliament-2015/homelessness-reduction-bill-report-published-16-17/|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> After receiving Government support at 2nd Reading, it passed through all stages in Parliament unopposed in both Houses and received [[Royal Assent]] on Thursday 27 April 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Homelessness Reduction Bill|url=http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2016-17/homelessnessreduction.html|work=[[UK Parliament]]|access-date=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610061858/http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2016-17/homelessnessreduction.html|archive-date=10 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2000, it was made public that Blackman had had an 11-year affair (which began in the late 80s) with a \ncolleague he met whilst working as a councillor at the Brent East Conservative Association. His then \nmistress, Carol Shaw, gave an [[affidavit]] about their affair to a solicitor in 2000 - after being \npersuaded to do so by one of Blackman's rivals who hoped to see him ousted as a group leader. The \n[[affidavit]] was copied and distributed amongst his fellow [[Conservative]] councillors by the rival. Blackman is married to former Conservative Party councillor Nicola Blackman, and the couple live in [[Wembley]]. He employs his wife as a part-time office manager on a salary up to \u00a339,999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/bob-blackman/|title=IPSA|publisher=GOV.UK|accessdate=7 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926034305/http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/bob-blackman/|archive-date=26 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Honours and Awards ==\n\n* [[File:IND_Padma_Shri_BAR.png|45x45px]] '''2020''': [[Padma Shri]] of India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/uk-tory-party-bob-blackman-padamshri-dedicates-indian-diaspora-1641425-2020-01-30|title=British leader and 4 time MP from Conservative Party Bob Blackman dedicates his Padam Shri to Indian diaspora|last=T|first=Loveena|last2=LondonJanuary 30|first2=on|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25|last3=January 30|first3=2020UPDATED|last4=Ist|first4=2020 00:25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bobblackmanmp.com/ Bob Blackman's website]\n{{UK MP links | parliament = bob-blackman/4005 | hansardcurr = 5580 | guardian = 9149/bob-blackman | publicwhip = Bob_Blackman | theywork = bob_blackman}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tony McNulty]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title =[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]]\n |years=[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Conservative Party UK MPs}}\n{{London Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{Template:Padma Shri Award Recipients in Public Affairs}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blackman, Bob}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:British Telecom people]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Brent]]\n[[Category:Conservative Members of the London Assembly]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:School governors]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in public affairs]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Bob Blackman\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Bob Blackman MP crop 2.jpg\n| caption = Blackman in 2020\n| office = Executive Secretary of the [[1922 Committee]]\n| leader = [[David Cameron]]<br />[[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 17 May 2012\n| alongside = [[Nigel Evans]] (2017-2020)\n| successor = \n| predecessor = [[Peter Bone]] &<br />[[Christopher Chope|Sir Christopher Chope]]\n| 1blankname = Chairman\n| 1namedata = [[Graham Brady|Sir Graham Brady]]<br />[[Cheryl Gillan]]<br />[[Charles Walker (British politician)|Charles Walker]]\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]]\n| majority2 = 8,170 (16.5%)\n| predecessor2 = [[Tony McNulty]]\n| successor2 = \n| term_start2 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end2 = \n| constituency_AM3 = [[Brent and Harrow (London Assembly constituency)|Brent and Harrow]]\n| assembly3 = London\n| term_start3 = 10 June 2004\n| term_end3 = 1 May 2008\n| predecessor3 = [[Toby Harris, Baron Harris of Haringey|Toby Harris]]\n| successor3 = [[Navin Shah]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1956|04|26}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/37675.stm |title=Bob Blackman MP |publisher=BBC |work=BBC Democracy Live |date= |accessdate=25 July 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917000831/http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/37675.stm |archive-date=17 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Metropolitan Borough of Kensington|Kensington]], London, England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Nicola Blackman\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = [[Wembley]], [[London]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Liverpool]]<br /><small> ([[Physics]] and [[Mathematics]] <br />[[Bachelor's degree]])</small>\n| occupation = \n| profession = [[BT Group|BT]]<br />[[telecommunications]] engineer\n| signature = \n| website = [http://www.bobblackmanmp.com/ bobblackmanmp.com]<br />[http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/bob-blackman/4005 parliament.uk biography]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Robert John Blackman''' (born 26 April 1956) is a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician serving as the Executive Secretary of the [[1922 Committee]] since 2012 (serving jointly with [[Nigel Evans]] until 8th January 2020 when Nigel became 2nd Deputy Chairman of Ways and Means),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18093877|title=New faces on Tory 1922 committee|date=17 May 2012|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=30 December 2017|via=www.bbc.co.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517085542/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-18093877|archive-date=17 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> and has served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]] since [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]. He was also the [[Greater London Assembly]] member for [[Brent and Harrow (London Assembly constituency)|Brent & Harrow]] between 2004 and 2008.\n\nHe is the recipient of India's highly prestigious award [[Padma Shri]] 2020 for his work in the field of public affairs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Padma Awards 2020 Announced |url=https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=197647 |website=pib.gov.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Desk |first1=The Hindu Net |title=Full list of 2020 Padma awardees |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/full-list-of-2020-padma-awardees/article30656841.ece |work=The Hindu |date=26 January 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nHe studied at the [[University of Liverpool]], where he was president of the [[students' union]]. He joined the sales team of Burroughs Machines (later [[Unisys]]) on graduation. He worked in various sales and management positions for [[BT Group plc|BT]] and worked at their training school in [[Milton Keynes]] as a tutor<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://www.bobblackmanmp.com/about/biography|website=Bob Blackman|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205213929/http://bobblackmanmp.com/about/biography|archive-date=5 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and later as a Regulatory Compliance Manager for BT<ref name=\"DeHaviland\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dehavilland.co.uk/VERTICALS/userlogin2.aspx?ReturnUrl=%2fVERTICALS%2fMonitor%2fMoStart.aspx%3fitems%3d18540349&items=18540349|title=Blackman responds to statement on the Leveson Inquiry|work=DeHaviland|accessdate=7 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105012508/http://www.dehavilland.co.uk/VERTICALS/userlogin2.aspx?ReturnUrl=%2fVERTICALS%2fMonitor%2fMoStart.aspx%3fitems%3d18540349&items=18540349|archive-date=5 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> until his election to Parliament.\n\n==Political career==\nBlackman unsuccessfully stood as the Conservative candidate in the Tokyngton ward of [[London Borough of Brent]] Council in 1986. Four years later, he stood in the [[Preston, London|Preston ward]] and was elected; he retained the seat until 2010, when he did not stand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Brent-1964-2010.pdf|title=London Borough of Brent Election Results 1964-2010|publisher=Plymouth University|accessdate=7 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612142902/http://www.electionscentre.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Brent-1964-2010.pdf|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He was the leader of the Conservative group on Brent council from 1990 to 2010, having been council leader between 1991 and 1996, when his party lost control of the Council. From June 2006 to May 2010, he was Deputy Leader of Brent Council, the Conservatives having formed a coalition with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].\n\nHe unsuccessfully stood as the Conservative Party parliamentary candidate for [[Brent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent South]] at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 election]], for [[Bedford (UK Parliament constituency)|Bedford]] at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 election]], and for [[Brent North (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent North]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 election]].\n\nHe unsuccessfully stood as the Conservative Party candidate for the constituency seat of [[Brent and Harrow (London Assembly constituency)|Brent and Harrow]] of the [[London Assembly]] at the [[2000 London Assembly election|2000 elections]], losing to the Labour Party candidate [[Toby Harris]]. However, he subsequently defeated Harris at the [[2004 London Assembly election|2004 assembly elections]] and was elected as the Conservative's [[Whip (politics)|Group Whip]] on the London Assembly. In the [[2008 London Assembly election|2008 elections]], Blackman lost his seat to the Labour candidate, [[Navin Shah]] by a 1,649 votes.<ref name=\"BBC2008lonresult\">{{Cite news | title = Brent & Harrow 2008 Election Result | publisher = BBC News | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/bsp/hi/elections/london/08/html/3.stm | date = 11 June 2008 | accessdate = 8 January 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120425062400/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/bsp/hi/elections/london/08/html/3.stm | archive-date = 25 April 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament==\nIn the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], Blackman gained the [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]] constituency from [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour's]] [[Tony McNulty]]. He was subsequently re-elected in 2015 and 2017.\n\nIn 2010 he was elected a member of the [[Communities and Local Government Committee|Communities and Local Government Select Committee]].<ref name=\"ParliamentBlackman\">{{cite web | title = Communities and Local Government Select Committee | publisher = UK Parliament | work = UK Parliament Website | url = http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/communities-and-local-government-committee/membership/ | date =  | accessdate = 8 January 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120118050938/http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/communities-and-local-government-committee/membership/ | archive-date = 18 January 2012 | url-status = live }}[]</ref> and was elected Secretary of the [[1922 Committee]] in 2015.<ref name=\"ConHome\">{{cite web | title = 1922 Committee Results | publisher = Conservative Home | work = Conservative Home Website | url = http://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2015/06/the-full-results-of-the-latest-1922-committee-election.html | date =  | accessdate = 25 April 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170426152225/http://www.conservativehome.com/parliament/2015/06/the-full-results-of-the-latest-1922-committee-election.html | archive-date = 26 April 2017 | url-status = live }}</ref> In Parliament, Blackman currently serves on the Procedure Committee, the Backbench Business Committee and the Housing, Communities and Local Government Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/bob-blackman/4005|title=Bob Blackman MP|publisher=GOV.UK|accessdate=7 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143858/https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/bob-blackman/4005|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, the Labour Party unsuccessfully proposed an amendment in Parliament that would have required private landlords to make their homes \"fit for human habitation\". According to Parliament's register of interests, Blackman was one of 72 Conservative MPs voting against the amendment who personally derived an income from renting out property. The Conservative Government had responded to the amendment that they believed homes should be fit for human habitation but did not want to pass the new law that would explicitly require it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tories vote down law requiring landlords make their homes fit for human habitation|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tories-vote-down-law-requiring-landlords-make-their-homes-fit-for-human-habitation-a6809691.html|work=[[The Independent|Independent]]|accessdate=18 September 2018|date=9 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180906032222/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tories-vote-down-law-requiring-landlords-make-their-homes-fit-for-human-habitation-a6809691.html|archive-date=6 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBlackman supported [[Brexit]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough|first1=Tom|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence?|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|accessdate=11 October 2016|work=The Spectator|date=16 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502030758/https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|archive-date=2 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He subsequently joined the [[European Research Group]] \u2013 the primary Eurosceptic lobbying group within Parliament, which is currently chaired by [[Jacob Rees-Mogg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/371977491/Letter-from-European-Research-Group-to-PM-May#from_embed|title=Letter from European Research Group to PM May|accessdate=21 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302201212/https://www.scribd.com/document/371977491/Letter-from-European-Research-Group-to-PM-May#from_embed|archive-date=2 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBlackman is an Officer of the [[Conservative Friends of Israel]] group and has been part of several delegations to Israel,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.cfoi.co.uk/Delegations/RecentDelegations/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-07-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727005934/http://www2.cfoi.co.uk/Delegations/RecentDelegations/ |archivedate=27 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> including during the [[Operation Defensive Shield]] conflict when he visited for an Israeli military briefing on the Iron Dome defence system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/30/tory-mps-visit-israel-condemned-bad-timing|title=Tory MPs' visit to Israel condemned as bad timing|first1=Rowena|last1=Mason|date=30 July 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=16 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126110223/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jul/30/tory-mps-visit-israel-condemned-bad-timing|archive-date=26 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the Compliance Officer for the [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority]] (IPSA) made a judgement that Blackman had submitted 732 inaccurate mileage claims.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Datoo|first1=Siraj|title=Tory MP Pays Back His Expenses After Making 734 \"Inaccurate\" Claims|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-31129900|publisher=BBC|date=4 February 2015|access-date=20 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109230544/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-31129900|archive-date=9 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to IPSA he claimed up to 10 miles for a 2-mile journey, making him the highest mileage MP, claiming almost twice the mileage as the 10 next highest MPs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11389305/Tory-MP-Bob-Blackmans-700-inaccurate-expenses-claims.html|title=Tory MP Bob Blackman's 700 'inaccurate expenses claims'|work=Daily Telegraph|date=4 February 2015|accessdate=4 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180915122542/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/11389305/Tory-MP-Bob-Blackmans-700-inaccurate-expenses-claims.html|archive-date=15 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBlackman has been accused{{by whom|date=January 2019}} of stirring up racial tensions as a result of racial bias for hosting Tapan Gosh, an anti-Islam campaigner from India at a [[House of Commons]] event in October 2017,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/anti-islam-tapan-ghosh-bob-blackman-rohingya-muslims-a8020656.html|title=Anti-Islam extremist who praised Rohingya massacre hosted in Commons|date=26 October 2017|work=The Independent|accessdate=30 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109114207/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/anti-islam-tapan-ghosh-bob-blackman-rohingya-muslims-a8020656.html|archive-date=9 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as sharing Islamophobic posts on Twitter by far-right activist [[Tommy Robinson (activist)|Tommy Robinson]] and being a member of numerous anti-Islam groups on Facebook.<ref name=\"Fisher2018\">{{cite news |last1=Fisher |first1=Lucy |title=Muslim Council of Britain demands inquiry into Tory 'Islamophobia' |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/muslim-council-of-britain-demands-inquiry-into-tory-islamophobia-jb6tw88sk |accessdate=14 August 2018 |work=The Times |date=31 May 2018 |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815055259/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/muslim-council-of-britain-demands-inquiry-into-tory-islamophobia-jb6tw88sk |archive-date=15 August 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> These comments and others by Conservative candidates and representatives led the [[Muslim Council of Britain]] to call for an [[Islamophobia in the UK Conservative Party#Calls for an independent inquiry|independent inquiry into alleged Islamophobia in the Conservative Party]].<ref name=\"Fisher2018\" />\n\nIn March 2019, Blackman was among a group of MPs who argued for a number of measures to encourage people to quit [[smoking]] and prevent young people from taking it up, including raising the legal [[smoking age]] to 21 and introducing a levy on [[Big Tobacco|large tobacco companies]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Jamie Doward |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/mar/02/raise-legal-smoking-age-to-21-say-mps |title=MPs call for legal smoking age to be raised to 21 &#124; Society |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2019-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191024134235/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2019/mar/02/raise-legal-smoking-age-to-21-say-mps |archive-date=24 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Blackman expressed his support for Indian [[Narendra Modi|Prime Minister Narendra Modi]] revoking [[Article 370 of the Constitution of India]], calling the article an \"anomaly\", adding that \"[[Kashmiri Pandits]] must be guaranteed right of return after they were the victims of ethnic cleansing\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/17831849.bob-blackman-harrow-east-mp-shares-thoughts-article-370/ |title=Bob Blackman, Harrow East MP, shares thoughts on Article 370 |publisher=Harrow Times |date=2019-08-12 |accessdate=2019-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191024104540/https://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/17831849.bob-blackman-harrow-east-mp-shares-thoughts-article-370/ |archive-date=24 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Campaigns==\nBlackman called for the adoption of plain packaging legislation for cigarettes,<ref name=\"Emma Innes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10081729.Harrow_MP_calls_for_cigarettes_to_be_sold_in_plain_packets/|title=Harrow MP calls for cigarettes to be sold in plain packets (From Harrow Times)|last=Emma Innes|date=30 November 2012|accessdate=7 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031019/http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10081729.Harrow_MP_calls_for_cigarettes_to_be_sold_in_plain_packets/|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and supported Cameron's plan calling for energy companies to provide simplified energy bills to their customers.<ref name=\"energy\">{{cite news|url=http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10060598.Harrow_East_MP_supports_government_energy_plans/|title=Harrow East MP supports government energy plans (From Harrow Times)|last=Emma Innes|date=21 November 2012|accessdate=7 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234819/http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10060598.Harrow_East_MP_supports_government_energy_plans/|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\nOn 1 July 2015, Blackman was elected Chair of the All Party Political Group on Smoking and Health, after serving as its Secretary for several years.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blackman|first1=Bob|title=Delighted to be elected Chairman of APPG for Action on Smoking & Health|url=https://twitter.com/bobblackmanmp/status/616392556990103553|publisher=Twitter|date=2 July 2015|access-date=2 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305214317/https://twitter.com/bobblackmanmp/status/616392556990103553|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170106/smoking-and-health.htm|title=Register Of All-Party Parliamentary Groups [as at 6 January 2017]|work=Parliament.uk|accessdate=22 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323142850/https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/170106/smoking-and-health.htm|archive-date=23 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] announced his approval for same-sex marriage.<ref name=\"BBC News\">{{Cite journal | title = Gay marriage: David Cameron backs church role | publisher = BBC | journal = BBC News | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20642428 | date = 6 December 2012 | accessdate = 6 December 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121207192535/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-20642428 | archive-date = 7 December 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref> In response, on 7 December 2012, Blackman told the [[BBC News Channel]] that David Cameron's backing of religious same-sex marriages was wrong \"on principle\" and that marriage had to be \"between one man and one woman\".<ref>Joe Murphy, \"Anti-homosexual Section 28 was right for schools, says Tory MP\", ''London Evening Standard'', 10 December 2012 [https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/antihomosexual-section-28-was-right-for-schools-says-tory-mp-8398942.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150601025652/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/antihomosexual-section-28-was-right-for-schools-says-tory-mp-8398942.html |date=1 June 2015 }}</ref> According to the ''Harrow Times'', he was accused of [[hypocrisy]] by a former fellow Brent council colleague who claimed she had an 11-year affair with him whilst he was married.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10112195.MP_at_heart_of_national_newspaper_storm|title=Harrow East MP Bob Blackman at heart of national newspaper storm|author=Emma Innes|work=Harrow Times|date=17 December 2012|accessdate=25 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126042509/http://www.harrowtimes.co.uk/news/10112195.MP_at_heart_of_national_newspaper_storm/|archive-date=26 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 February 2013, Bob Blackman voted against the bill in the House of Commons Second Reading vote on marriage equality in Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130205/debtext/130205-0004.htm|title=The House of Commons.2013.Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Bill 2012\u20132013.|website=publications.parliament.uk|access-date=12 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115021159/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130205/debtext/130205-0004.htm|archive-date=15 November 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, when the Conservative Party launched its consultation into legalising same-sex marriages, Blackman suggested that [[David Cameron]] should resurrect [[Section 28]], stating that he strongly believed that \"Section 28 was the right rules to have in school so that we should not in any way shape or form promote same-sex relationships\" and said he would be \"very opposed\" to seeing teachers being forced to say same-sex relationships are equivalent to heterosexual relationships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/12/07/tory-mp-bob-blackman-cameron-should-be-re-introducing-section-28-not-letting-gays-marry/|title=Tory MP Bob Blackman: Cameron should be re-introducing Section 28 not letting gays marry|publisher=|accessdate=30 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131224545/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/12/07/tory-mp-bob-blackman-cameron-should-be-re-introducing-section-28-not-letting-gays-marry/|archive-date=31 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Blackman was one of 21 MPs who voted against LGBT inclusive sex and relationship education in English schools.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/education/lgbt-sex-relationship-education-mps-support/ |title=MPs vote for LGBT inclusive sex and relationship education from primary school |publisher=inews |date= |accessdate=2019-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330104814/https://inews.co.uk/news/education/lgbt-sex-relationship-education-mps-support/ |archive-date=30 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/21-mps-who-voted-against-14198149 |title=Archived copy |access-date=30 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330093652/https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/21-mps-who-voted-against-14198149 |archive-date=30 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://commonsvotes.digiminster.com/Divisions/Details/650#noes |title=Draft Relationships Education, Relationships and Sex Education and Health Education (England) Regulations 2019 - CommonsVotes |publisher=Commonsvotes.digiminster.com |date=2019-03-27 |accessdate=2019-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329025226/https://commonsvotes.digiminster.com/Divisions/Details/650#noes |archive-date=29 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he was drawn second in the annual Parliamentary ballot for a [[Private Member's Bill]] and subsequently put together a Homelessness Reduction Bill in partnership with national homelessness charity, [[Crisis (charity)|Crisis]].<ref name=\"Crisis Report\">{{cite web | title = No One Turned Away | publisher = Crisis | url = https://community.crisis.org.uk/no-one-turned-away/home | date =  | accessdate = 25 April 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170426151613/https://community.crisis.org.uk/no-one-turned-away/home | archive-date = 26 April 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref> It was the first Private Member's Bill to be supported by a Select Committee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Homelessness Reduction Bill supported by Committee|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/communities-and-local-government-committee/news-parliament-2015/homelessness-reduction-bill-report-published-16-17/|work=[[UK Parliament]]|date=14 October 2016|access-date=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170426152201/http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/communities-and-local-government-committee/news-parliament-2015/homelessness-reduction-bill-report-published-16-17/|archive-date=26 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> After receiving Government support at 2nd Reading, it passed through all stages in Parliament unopposed in both Houses and received [[Royal Assent]] on Thursday 27 April 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Homelessness Reduction Bill|url=http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2016-17/homelessnessreduction.html|work=[[UK Parliament]]|access-date=25 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610061858/http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2016-17/homelessnessreduction.html|archive-date=10 June 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2000, it was made public that Blackman had had an 11 year affair (which began in the late 80s) with a \ncolleague he met whilst working as a councillor at the Brent East Conservative Association. His then \nmistress, Carol Shaw, gave an [[affidavit]] about their affair to a solicitor in 2000 - after being \npersuaded to do so by one of Blackman's rivals who hoped to see him ousted as a group leader. The \n[[affidavit]] was copied and distributed amongst his fellow [[Conservative]] councillors by the rival. Blackman is married to former Conservative Party councillor Nicola Blackman, and the couple live in [[Wembley]]. He employs his wife as a part-time office manager on a salary up to \u00a339,999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/bob-blackman/|title=IPSA|publisher=GOV.UK|accessdate=7 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926034305/http://www.theipsa.org.uk/mp-costs/your-mp/bob-blackman/|archive-date=26 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Honours and Awards ==\n\n* [[File:IND_Padma_Shri_BAR.png|45x45px]] '''2020''': [[Padma Shri]] of India<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/uk-tory-party-bob-blackman-padamshri-dedicates-indian-diaspora-1641425-2020-01-30|title=British leader and 4 time MP from Conservative Party Bob Blackman dedicates his Padam Shri to Indian diaspora|last=T|first=Loveena|last2=LondonJanuary 30|first2=on|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-02-25|last3=January 30|first3=2020UPDATED|last4=Ist|first4=2020 00:25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bobblackmanmp.com/ Bob Blackman's website]\n{{UK MP links | parliament = bob-blackman/4005 | hansardcurr = 5580 | guardian = 9149/bob-blackman | publicwhip = Bob_Blackman | theywork = bob_blackman}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tony McNulty]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n |title =[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]]\n |years=[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Conservative Party UK MPs}}\n{{London Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{Template:Padma Shri Award Recipients in Public Affairs}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blackman, Bob}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:British Telecom people]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Brent]]\n[[Category:Conservative Members of the London Assembly]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:School governors]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in public affairs]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 11 year \u2192 11-year", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Blackman"}
{"title_page": "Jawdat Al-Qazwini", "text_new": "{{short description|Iraqi scholar and poet}}\n{{notability|Academics|date=July 2013}}\n\n'''Jawdat Al-Qazwini''' (1953 \u2013 April 7, 2020) was an [[Iraqi people|Iraqi]] scholar. He studied in the academic and traditional fields in [[Najaf]] and [[Karbala]]. He traveled around different Iraqi cities, seeking biographies of great scholars from different [[sects]]. This work also led him to travel to other countries, including Egypt, Syria, Iran and India.\n\n==Education==\nAl-Qazwini studied for his M.A. in Cairo, Egypt and his PhD at [[SOAS, University of London|SOAS University, London]].\n\n==References==\n#[https://archive.today/20130503064849/http://www.iraqiwelfare.org/?p=13&id=5&cat=module&sub=news&lang=ar \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0647\u062c\u0631]\n#[https://web.archive.org/web/20160303204000/http://www.iraqiwelfare.org/admin/files/editor/uploads/files/Documents/AlMahjer%2047%2026-48.pdf \u0645\u0644\u0641 \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0647\u062c\u0631]\n#[http://www.yahosein.com/vb/showthread.php?t=159247 \u0645\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645\u0627\u062a \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0639\u0646\u0647]\n#A selfbiography for Dr. J Al-Qazwini published in the Journal of the season, see: ''mawsim'' Magazine Issue Year 1411 - No. 9,10 [http://www.noormags.com/view/fa/articlepage/27326/651/text ]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qazwini, Jawdat Al-}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:Iraqi scholars]]\n[[Category:21st-century Iraqi poets]]\n\n\n{{Iraq-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Iraqi scholar and poet}}\n{{notability|Academics|date=July 2013}}\n\n'''Jawdat Al-Qazwini''' (1953 - April 7, 2020) was an [[Iraqi people|Iraqi]] scholar. He studied in the academic and traditional fields in [[Najaf]] and [[Karbala]]. He traveled around different Iraqi cities, seeking biographies of great scholars from different [[sects]]. This work also led him to travel to other countries, including Egypt, Syria, Iran and India.\n\n==Education==\nAl-Qazwini studied for his M.A. in Cairo, Egypt and his PhD at [[SOAS, University of London|SOAS University, London]].\n\n==References==\n#[https://archive.today/20130503064849/http://www.iraqiwelfare.org/?p=13&id=5&cat=module&sub=news&lang=ar \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0647\u062c\u0631]\n#[https://web.archive.org/web/20160303204000/http://www.iraqiwelfare.org/admin/files/editor/uploads/files/Documents/AlMahjer%2047%2026-48.pdf \u0645\u0644\u0641 \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0647\u062c\u0631]\n#[http://www.yahosein.com/vb/showthread.php?t=159247 \u0645\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645\u0627\u062a \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0639\u0646\u0647]\n#A selfbiography for Dr. J Al-Qazwini published in the Journal of the season, see: ''mawsim'' Magazine Issue Year 1411 - No. 9,10 [http://www.noormags.com/view/fa/articlepage/27326/651/text ]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qazwini, Jawdat Al-}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:Iraqi scholars]]\n[[Category:21st-century Iraqi poets]]\n\n\n{{Iraq-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Brycehughes", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jawdat_Al-Qazwini"}
{"title_page": "Stephen Barclay", "text_new": "{{For|other uses|Steve Barclay (disambiguation)}}\n{{Short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Stephen Barclay\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Steve Barclay MP crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| status = \n| term_start = 13 February 2020\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Rishi Sunak]]\n| office1 = [[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| status1 = \n| term_start1 = 16 November 2018\n| term_end1 = 31 January 2020\n| predecessor1 = [[Dominic Raab]]\n| successor1 = ''Position abolished''\n| office2 = [[Department of Health and Social Care|Minister of State for Health]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start2 = 9 January 2018\n| term_end2 = 16 November 2018\n| predecessor2 = [[Philip Dunne (Ludlow MP)|Philip Dunne]]\n| successor2 = [[Stephen Hammond]]\n| office3 = [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start3 = 14 June 2017\n| term_end3 = 9 January 2018\n| predecessor3 = [[Simon Kirby]]\n| successor3 = [[John Glen (politician)|John Glen]]\n| office4 = [[Lords Commissioners of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start4 = 17 July 2016\n| term_end4 = 14 June 2017\n| predecessor4 = [[George Hollingbery]]\n| successor4 = [[David Rutley]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[North East Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Cambridgeshire]]\n| term_start5 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end5 = \n| predecessor5 = [[Malcolm Moss]]\n| successor5 = \n| majority5 = 29,993 (56.6%)\n| birth_name = Stephen Paul Barclay\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|05|03|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lytham St Annes]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| education = [[King Edward VII and Queen Mary School|King Edward VII School]]\n| alma_mater = [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n| profession = [[Solicitor]]\n| spouse = Karen\n| children = 3\n| website = {{url|http://stevebarclay.net|Official website}}\n<!--Military service-->| allegiance = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| branch = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n| serviceyears = 1991\n| rank = [[Second lieutenant]]\n| unit = [[Royal Regiment of Fusiliers]]\n| caption = Barclay in 2020\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Paul \"Steve\" Barclay''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|PC|MP}} (born 3 May 1972)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61230 |date=18 May 2015 |page=9120}}</ref><ref name=\"Who's Who\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.251452|title=Barclay, Stephen Paul, (born 1972), MP (C) North East Cambridgeshire, since 2010; Economic Secretary to HM Treasury, since 2017 |journal=Who's Who |year=2010}}</ref> is a British politician who has been [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]] since February 2020 and previously served as [[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]] from November 2018 until January 2020. A member of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], he has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[North East Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Cambridgeshire]] since [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]].<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Wisbech Standard |url=http://www.wisbech-standard.co.uk/content/wisbech/news/story.aspx?brand=CATOnline&category=NewsWisbech&tBrand=HertsCambsOnline&tCategory=newslatestWIS&itemid=WEED07%20May%202010%2003%3A46%3A36%3A540 |title=3.46AM: Stephen Barclay wins NE Cambs seat and extends Tory majority to more than 16,000 |date=7 May 2010 |accessdate=8 May 2010}}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/10DowningStreet/status/1063469503210811392 |title=The Queen has been pleased to approve the appointment of Stephen Barclay MP @SteveBarclay to be Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union @DExEUgov |last= |first= |date= |website=Twitter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116215804/https://twitter.com/10downingstreet/status/1063469503210811392 |archive-date=16 November 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=16 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\nBarclay served as [[Lords Commissioners of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]] from 2016 to 2017 and [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]] from 2017 until 2018. After the [[2018 British cabinet reshuffle|January 2018 cabinet reshuffle]], he became [[Minister of State]] at the [[Department of Health and Social Care]]; Barclay was appointed Brexit Secretary in November that year following the resignation of [[Dominic Raab]]. He remained in office until Britain left the EU in January 2020; he then became [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBarclay was brought up in Lancashire. His father worked as a full-time [[trade union]] official and then in IT, and his mother worked full-time as a [[civil service]] administrator.<ref name=\"conhome\">{{cite web|title=Steve Barclay |url=https://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Members_of_Parliament/Barclay_Stephen.aspx |website=Conservative Home |access-date=18 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140516195359/http://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Members_of_Parliament/Barclay_Stephen.aspx |archive-date=16 May 2014 |df= }}</ref>\nHe is the youngest of three brothers, all of whom played rugby.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/candidate-profile-steve-barclay-1-4028795 |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022082812/https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/candidate-profile-steve-barclay-1-4028795 |archive-date=22 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBarclay was educated at [[King Edward VII and Queen Mary School|King Edward VII School]], an [[independent school]] in [[Lytham St Annes]]. After completing his [[GCE Advanced Level|A levels]], he joined the [[British Army]] on a Gap Year Commission, attended the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]], and served as a Second Lieutenant with the [[Royal Regiment of Fusiliers]] for five months.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52531 |date=13 May 1991 |page=7432 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52707 |date=4 November 1991 |page=16855 |supp=y}}</ref> His is the first generation of his family to go to university, and he read history at [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]]. He then studied at the [[Chester]] [[University of Law|College of Law]] [[campus]], to qualify as a solicitor in 1998.<ref name=\"conhome\" />\n\n==Early career==\nBarclay completed his [[training contract]] as an [[articled clerk]] with a large London law firm before working at Royal Exchange, [[AXA|Axa Insurance]], the [[Financial Services Authority]], and [[Barclays]], where he was the head of Anti-Money Laundering and Sanctions for the retail banking division.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stevebarclay.net/?page_id=7 |title=Biography |publisher=stevebarclay.net |date= |access-date=17 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509073802/http://stevebarclay.net/?page_id=7 |archive-date=9 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nAfter leaving university in 1994, Barclay joined the Conservative Party.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barclay|first1=Steve|title=Biography|url=http://stevebarclay.net/biography/|accessdate=17 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320060712/http://stevebarclay.net/biography/|archive-date=20 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He was a member of [[A-List (Conservative)|the A-List]] and was twice an unsuccessful parliamentary candidate, contesting [[Manchester Blackley (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester Blackley]] in [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] and [[Lancaster and Wyre (UK Parliament constituency)|Lancaster & Wyre]] in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]], coming within 500 votes of winning the latter seat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/04/the-18-of-the-original-100-alisters-selected-for-conservative-seats-.html|title=ConservativeHome's Seats & Candidates blog: Where are the original A-Listers now? The 18 who have been selected for Conservative seats|publisher=|access-date=6 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028112024/http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/04/the-18-of-the-original-100-alisters-selected-for-conservative-seats-.html|archive-date=28 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2007, Barclay took over as the organiser of the [[Carlton Club]] political dinner, which raises funds for the Conservative Party's target seats.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nBarclay was selected in January 2008 to replace the outgoing North East Cambridgeshire MP, [[Malcolm Moss]], and was elected at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|May 2010 general election]] with a majority of 16,425. After the election, he was soon elected by fellow MPs to become a member of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]], which scrutinises government spending.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/public-accounts-committee/membership/ |title=Public Accounts Committee - Membership |publisher=parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=17 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118192341/http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/public-accounts-committee/membership/ |archive-date=18 November 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[Conservative Home]] named him  as one of a minority of loyal Conservative backbench MPs not to have voted against the government in any substantive rebellions.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barrett|first1=Matthew|title=The 24 Conservative MPs who are still on the backbenches and have never rebelled|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/thetorydiary/2012/09/the-forty-non-government-payroll-mps-who-havent-rebelled.html|website=Conservative Home|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510203022/http://www.conservativehome.com/thetorydiary/2012/09/the-forty-non-government-payroll-mps-who-havent-rebelled.html|archive-date=10 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the appointment of [[Theresa May]] to [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], Barclay was appointed as a [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]. \n\nIn June 2017, Barclay joined [[HM Treasury]] as the [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]].  \n\nIn January 2018, he joined the [[Department for Health and Social Care]] as the [[Minister of State for Health]].\n\n===Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union===\nBarclay was appointed as [[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]] in November 2018 following the resignation of [[Dominic Raab]].<ref name=\"Barclay appointed\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-46241693 |title=Steve Barclay named new Brexit Secretary |date=16 November 2018 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=16 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116171435/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-46241693 |archive-date=16 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was reported that Barclay would focus on the domestic preparations rather than negotiations for [[Brexit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46241693|title=Stephen Barclay named new Brexit Secretary|date=2018-11-16|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-17|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118034205/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46241693|archive-date=18 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He retained his role as Brexit Secretary in [[Boris Johnson]]'s [[First Johnson ministry|first]] and [[Second Johnson ministry|second]] cabinets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/stephen-barclay-brexit-secretary-borisjohnson-16641255|title=MP Stephen Barclay holds on to Brexit secretary job in Boris' new cabinet|last=Leishman|first=Fiona|date=2019-07-24|website=cambridgenews|access-date=2019-07-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724210625/https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/stephen-barclay-brexit-secretary-borisjohnson-16641255|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He ceased to be Brexit Secretary at 11:01 pm on 31 January 2020, the moment the [[Department for Exiting the European Union]] was closed down.\n\n===Chief Secretary to the Treasury===\nBarclay was appointed as the [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]] in February 2020, replacing [[Rishi Sunak]] who had been appointed [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] following the surprise resignation of [[Sajid Javid]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBarclay and his wife Karen have a son and two daughters.<ref name=\"Who's Who\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140516195359/http://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Members_of_Parliament/Barclay_Stephen.aspx Profile] at the Conservative Party\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = stephen-barclay/4095 | hansardcurr = 5573 | guardian = 11998/stephen-barclay | publicwhip = Stephen_Barclay | theywork = stephen_barclay}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Malcolm Moss]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for<br />[[North East Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Cambridgeshire]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dominic Raab]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]|years=2018&ndash;2020}}\n{{s-non|reason=Office abolished}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rishi Sunak]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chief Secretaries to the Treasury}}\n{{Ministers at HM Treasury}}\n{{Johnson Cabinet}}\n{{Second May Cabinet}}\n{{East of England Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barclay, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Lytham St Annes]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Royal Regiment of Fusiliers officers]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:People educated at King Edward VII and Queen Mary School]]\n[[Category:Economic Secretaries to the Treasury]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Exiting the European Union]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other uses|Steve Barclay (disambiguation)}}\n{{Short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Stephen Barclay\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Steve Barclay MP crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| status = \n| term_start = 13 February 2020\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Rishi Sunak]]\n| office1 = [[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| status1 = \n| term_start1 = 16 November 2018\n| term_end1 = 31 January 2020\n| predecessor1 = [[Dominic Raab]]\n| successor1 = ''Position abolished''\n| office2 = [[Department of Health and Social Care|Minister of State for Health]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start2 = 9 January 2018\n| term_end2 = 16 November 2018\n| predecessor2 = [[Philip Dunne (Ludlow MP)|Philip Dunne]]\n| successor2 = [[Stephen Hammond]]\n| office3 = [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start3 = 14 June 2017\n| term_end3 = 9 January 2018\n| predecessor3 = [[Simon Kirby]]\n| successor3 = [[John Glen (politician)|John Glen]]\n| office4 = [[Lords Commissioners of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start4 = 17 July 2016\n| term_end4 = 14 June 2017\n| predecessor4 = [[George Hollingbery]]\n| successor4 = [[David Rutley]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[North East Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Cambridgeshire]]\n| term_start5 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end5 = \n| predecessor5 = [[Malcolm Moss]]\n| successor5 = \n| majority5 = 29,993 (56.6%)\n| birth_name = Stephen Paul Barclay\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|05|03|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lytham St Annes]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| education = [[King Edward VII and Queen Mary School|King Edward VII School]]\n| alma_mater = [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n| profession = [[Solicitor]]\n| spouse = Karen\n| children = 3\n| website = {{url|http://stevebarclay.net|Official website}}\n<!--Military service-->| allegiance = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| branch = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n| serviceyears = 1991\n| rank = [[Second lieutenant]]\n| unit = [[Royal Regiment of Fusiliers]]\n| caption = Barclay in 2020\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Paul \"Steve\" Barclay''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|PC|MP}} (born 3 May 1972)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61230 |date=18 May 2015 |page=9120}}</ref><ref name=\"Who's Who\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.251452|title=Barclay, Stephen Paul, (born 1972), MP (C) North East Cambridgeshire, since 2010; Economic Secretary to HM Treasury, since 2017 |journal=Who's Who |year=2010}}</ref> is a British politician who has been [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]] since February 2020 and previously served as [[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]] from November 2018 until January 2020. A member of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], he has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[North East Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Cambridgeshire]] since [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]].<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Wisbech Standard |url=http://www.wisbech-standard.co.uk/content/wisbech/news/story.aspx?brand=CATOnline&category=NewsWisbech&tBrand=HertsCambsOnline&tCategory=newslatestWIS&itemid=WEED07%20May%202010%2003%3A46%3A36%3A540 |title=3.46AM: Stephen Barclay wins NE Cambs seat and extends Tory majority to more than 16,000 |date=7 May 2010 |accessdate=8 May 2010}}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/10DowningStreet/status/1063469503210811392 |title=The Queen has been pleased to approve the appointment of Stephen Barclay MP @SteveBarclay to be Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union @DExEUgov |last= |first= |date= |website=Twitter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116215804/https://twitter.com/10downingstreet/status/1063469503210811392 |archive-date=16 November 2018 |url-status=live |access-date=16 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\nBarclay served as [[Lords Commissioners of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]] from 2016 to 2017 and [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]] from 2017 until 2018. After the [[2018 British cabinet reshuffle|January 2018 cabinet reshuffle]], he became [[Minister of State]] at the [[Department of Health and Social Care]]; Barclay was appointed Brexit Secretary in November that year following the resignation of [[Dominic Raab]]. He remained in office until Britain left the EU in January 2020; he then became [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBarclay was brought up in Lancashire. His father worked as a full time [[trade union]] official and then in IT, and his mother worked full time as a [[civil service]] administrator.<ref name=\"conhome\">{{cite web|title=Steve Barclay |url=https://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Members_of_Parliament/Barclay_Stephen.aspx |website=Conservative Home |access-date=18 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140516195359/http://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Members_of_Parliament/Barclay_Stephen.aspx |archive-date=16 May 2014 |df= }}</ref>\nHe is the youngest of three brothers, all of whom played rugby.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/candidate-profile-steve-barclay-1-4028795 |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022082812/https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/candidate-profile-steve-barclay-1-4028795 |archive-date=22 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBarclay was educated at [[King Edward VII and Queen Mary School|King Edward VII School]], an [[independent school]] in [[Lytham St Annes]]. After completing his [[GCE Advanced Level|A levels]], he joined the [[British Army]] on a Gap Year Commission, attended the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]], and served as a Second Lieutenant with the [[Royal Regiment of Fusiliers]] for five months.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52531 |date=13 May 1991 |page=7432 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52707 |date=4 November 1991 |page=16855 |supp=y}}</ref> His is the first generation of his family to go to university, and he read history at [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]]. He then studied at the [[Chester]] [[University of Law|College of Law]] [[campus]], to qualify as a solicitor in 1998.<ref name=\"conhome\" />\n\n==Early career==\nBarclay completed his [[training contract]] as an [[articled clerk]] with a large London law firm before working at Royal Exchange, [[AXA|Axa Insurance]], the [[Financial Services Authority]], and [[Barclays]], where he was the head of Anti-Money Laundering and Sanctions for the retail banking division.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stevebarclay.net/?page_id=7 |title=Biography |publisher=stevebarclay.net |date= |access-date=17 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509073802/http://stevebarclay.net/?page_id=7 |archive-date=9 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nAfter leaving university in 1994, Barclay joined the Conservative Party.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barclay|first1=Steve|title=Biography|url=http://stevebarclay.net/biography/|accessdate=17 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320060712/http://stevebarclay.net/biography/|archive-date=20 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He was a member of [[A-List (Conservative)|the A-List]] and was twice an unsuccessful parliamentary candidate, contesting [[Manchester Blackley (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester Blackley]] in [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] and [[Lancaster and Wyre (UK Parliament constituency)|Lancaster & Wyre]] in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]], coming within 500 votes of winning the latter seat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/04/the-18-of-the-original-100-alisters-selected-for-conservative-seats-.html|title=ConservativeHome's Seats & Candidates blog: Where are the original A-Listers now? The 18 who have been selected for Conservative seats|publisher=|access-date=6 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028112024/http://conservativehome.blogs.com/goldlist/2009/04/the-18-of-the-original-100-alisters-selected-for-conservative-seats-.html|archive-date=28 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2007, Barclay took over as the organiser of the [[Carlton Club]] political dinner, which raises funds for the Conservative Party\u2019s target seats.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nBarclay was selected in January 2008 to replace the outgoing North East Cambridgeshire MP, [[Malcolm Moss]], and was elected at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|May 2010 general election]] with a majority of 16,425. After the election, he was soon elected by fellow MPs to become a member of the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]], which scrutinises government spending.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/public-accounts-committee/membership/ |title=Public Accounts Committee - Membership |publisher=parliament.uk |date= |accessdate=17 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118192341/http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/public-accounts-committee/membership/ |archive-date=18 November 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[Conservative Home]] named him  as one of a minority of loyal Conservative backbench MPs not to have voted against the government in any substantive rebellions.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barrett|first1=Matthew|title=The 24 Conservative MPs who are still on the backbenches and have never rebelled|url=http://www.conservativehome.com/thetorydiary/2012/09/the-forty-non-government-payroll-mps-who-havent-rebelled.html|website=Conservative Home|accessdate=19 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510203022/http://www.conservativehome.com/thetorydiary/2012/09/the-forty-non-government-payroll-mps-who-havent-rebelled.html|archive-date=10 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the appointment of [[Theresa May]] to [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], Barclay was appointed as a [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]. \n\nIn June 2017, Barclay joined [[HM Treasury]] as the [[Economic Secretary to the Treasury]].  \n\nIn January 2018, he joined the [[Department for Health and Social Care]] as the [[Minister of State for Health]].\n\n===Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union===\nBarclay was appointed as [[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]] in November 2018 following the resignation of [[Dominic Raab]].<ref name=\"Barclay appointed\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-46241693 |title=Steve Barclay named new Brexit Secretary |date=16 November 2018 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=16 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116171435/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-46241693 |archive-date=16 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was reported that Barclay would focus on the domestic preparations rather than negotiations for [[Brexit]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46241693|title=Stephen Barclay named new Brexit Secretary|date=2018-11-16|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-17|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118034205/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46241693|archive-date=18 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He retained his role as Brexit Secretary in [[Boris Johnson]]'s [[First Johnson ministry|first]] and [[Second Johnson ministry|second]] cabinets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/stephen-barclay-brexit-secretary-borisjohnson-16641255|title=MP Stephen Barclay holds on to Brexit secretary job in Boris' new cabinet|last=Leishman|first=Fiona|date=2019-07-24|website=cambridgenews|access-date=2019-07-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724210625/https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/stephen-barclay-brexit-secretary-borisjohnson-16641255|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He ceased to be Brexit Secretary at 11:01 pm on 31 January 2020, the moment the [[Department for Exiting the European Union]] was closed down.\n\n===Chief Secretary to the Treasury===\nBarclay was appointed as the [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]] in February 2020, replacing [[Rishi Sunak]] who had been appointed [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] following the surprise resignation of [[Sajid Javid]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBarclay and his wife Karen have a son and two daughters.<ref name=\"Who's Who\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140516195359/http://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Members_of_Parliament/Barclay_Stephen.aspx Profile] at the Conservative Party\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = stephen-barclay/4095 | hansardcurr = 5573 | guardian = 11998/stephen-barclay | publicwhip = Stephen_Barclay | theywork = stephen_barclay}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Malcolm Moss]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for<br />[[North East Cambridgeshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North East Cambridgeshire]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dominic Raab]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]|years=2018&ndash;2020}}\n{{s-non|reason=Office abolished}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rishi Sunak]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chief Secretaries to the Treasury}}\n{{Ministers at HM Treasury}}\n{{Johnson Cabinet}}\n{{Second May Cabinet}}\n{{East of England Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barclay, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Peterhouse, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Lytham St Annes]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Royal Regiment of Fusiliers officers]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:People educated at King Edward VII and Queen Mary School]]\n[[Category:Economic Secretaries to the Treasury]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Exiting the European Union]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: full time \u2192 full-time (2), \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_Barclay"}
